# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grouped-query-attention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:grouped-query-attention/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:grouped-query-attention/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:grouped-query-attention/grouped-query-attention-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:grouped-query-attention/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The **softmax function,** also known as **softargmax** or **normalized exponential function**, converts a tuple of K real numbers into a probability distribution over K possible outcomes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] It is a generalization of the logistic function to multiple dimensions, and is used in multinomial logistic regression.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function is often used as the last activation function of a neural network to normalize the output of a network to a probability distribution over predicted output classes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function takes as input a tuple z of K real numbers, and normalizes it into a probability distribution consisting of K probabilities proportional to the exponentials of the input numbers.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] That is, prior to applying softmax, some tuple components could be negative, or greater than one; and might not sum to 1; but after applying softmax, each component will be in the interval $(0,1)$ , and the components will add up to 1, so that they can be interpreted as probabilities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Furthermore, the larger input components will correspond to larger probabilities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In words, the softmax applies the standard exponential function to each element $z_{i}$ of the input tuple $\mathbf {z}$ (consisting of K real numbers), and normalizes these values by dividing by the sum of all these exponentials.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The normalization ensures that the sum of the components of the output vector $\sigma (\mathbf {z} )$ is 1.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The term "softmax" derives from the amplifying effects of the exponential on any maxima in the input tuple.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] For example, the standard softmax of $(1,2,8)$ is approximately $(0.001,0.002,0.997)$ , which amounts to assigning almost all of the total unit weight in the result to the position of the tuple's maximal element (of 8).
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In general, instead of e a different base b > 0 can be used.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] As above, if b > 1 then larger input components will result in larger output probabilities, and increasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the largest input values.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Conversely, if 0 < b < 1 then smaller input components will result in larger output probabilities, and decreasing the value of b will create probability distributions that are more concentrated around the positions of the smallest input values.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] A value proportional to the reciprocal of β is sometimes referred to as the *temperature*: ${\textstyle \beta =1/kT}$ , where k is typically 1 or the Boltzmann constant and T is the temperature.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] A higher temperature results in a more uniform output distribution (i.e. with higher entropy; it is "more random"), while a lower temperature results in a sharper output distribution, with one value dominating.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In some fields, the base is fixed, corresponding to a fixed scale, while in others the parameter β (or T) is varied.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function is a multiple-variable generalization of the logistic function.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The Softmax function is a smooth approximation to the arg max function: the function whose value is the *index* of a tuple's largest element.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Softmax is not a smooth maximum (that is, a smooth approximation to the maximum function).
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The term "softmax" is also used for the closely related LogSumExp function, which is a smooth maximum.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] For this reason, some prefer the more accurate term "softargmax", though the term "softmax" is conventional in machine learning.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] This section uses the term "softargmax" for clarity.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] For example, in this encoding $\operatorname {arg\,max} (1,5,10)=(0,0,1),$ since the third argument is the maximum.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] This can be generalized to multiple arg max values (multiple equal $z_{i}$ being the maximum) by dividing the 1 between all max args; formally 1/k where k is the number of arguments assuming the maximum.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] With the last expression given in the introduction, softargmax is now a smooth approximation of arg max: as ⁠ $\beta \to \infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg max.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In fact, softargmax is continuous, but arg max is not continuous at the singular set where two coordinates are equal, while the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The reason it fails to converge uniformly is that for inputs where two coordinates are almost equal (and one is the maximum), the arg max is the index of one or the other, so a small change in input yields a large change in output.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] However, softargmax does converge compactly on the non-singular set.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Conversely, as ⁠ $\beta \to -\infty$ ⁠, softargmax converges to arg min in the same way, where here the singular set is points with two arg *min* values.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] It is also the case that, for any fixed β, if one input ⁠ $z_{i}$ ⁠ is much larger than the others *relative* to the temperature, $T=1/\beta$ , the output is approximately the arg max.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function is used in various multiclass classification methods, such as multinomial logistic regression (also known as softmax regression), multiclass linear discriminant analysis, naive Bayes classifiers, and artificial neural networks.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The operation is equivalent to applying a linear operator defined by $\mathbf {w}$ to tuples $\mathbf {x}$ , thus transforming the original, probably highly-dimensional, input to vectors in a K-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{K}$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The standard softmax function is often used in the final layer of a neural network-based classifier.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Such networks are commonly trained under a log loss (or cross-entropy) regime, giving a non-linear variant of multinomial logistic regression.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Here, the Kronecker delta is used for simplicity (cf. the derivative of a sigmoid function, being expressed via the function itself).
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] To ensure stable numerical computations subtracting the maximum value from the input tuple is common.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] This approach, while not altering the output or the derivative theoretically, enhances stability by directly controlling the maximum exponent value computed.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] If the function is scaled with the parameter $\beta$ , then these expressions must be multiplied by $\beta$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] See multinomial logit for a probability model which uses the softmax activation function.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In the field of reinforcement learning, a softmax function can be used to convert values into action probabilities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] where the action value $q_{t}(a)$ corresponds to the expected reward of following action a and $\tau$ is called a temperature parameter (in allusion to statistical mechanics).
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] For high temperatures ( $\tau \to \infty$ ), all actions have nearly the same probability and the lower the temperature, the more expected rewards affect the probability.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] For a low temperature ( $\tau \to 0^{+}$ ), the probability of the action with the highest expected reward tends to 1.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In neural network applications, the number K of possible outcomes is often large, e.g. in case of neural language models that predict the most likely outcome out of a vocabulary which might contain millions of possible words.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] This can make the calculations for the softmax layer (i.e. the matrix multiplications to determine the $z_{i}$ , followed by the application of the softmax function itself) computationally expensive.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] What's more, the gradient descent backpropagation method for training such a neural network involves calculating the softmax for every training example, and the number of training examples can also become large.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The computational effort for the softmax became a major limiting factor in the development of larger neural language models, motivating various remedies to reduce training times.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Approaches that reorganize the softmax layer for more efficient calculation include the **hierarchical softmax** and the **differentiated softmax**.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The hierarchical softmax (introduced by Morin and Bengio in 2005) uses a binary tree structure where the outcomes (vocabulary words) are the leaves and the intermediate nodes are suitably selected "classes" of outcomes, forming latent variables.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The desired probability (softmax value) of a leaf (outcome) can then be calculated as the product of the probabilities of all nodes on the path from the root to that leaf.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Ideally, when the tree is balanced, this would reduce the computational complexity from $O(K)$ to $O(\log _{2}K)$ .
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In practice, results depend on choosing a good strategy for clustering the outcomes into classes.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] A Huffman tree was used for this in Google's word2vec models (introduced in 2013) to achieve scalability.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] A second kind of remedies is based on approximating the softmax (during training) with modified loss functions that avoid the calculation of the full normalization factor.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] These include methods that restrict the normalization sum to a sample of outcomes (e.g.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The standard softmax is numerically unstable because of large exponentiations.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Subtracting by it guarantees that the exponentiations result in at most 1, see translation invariance in the mathematical properties.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] It can be efficiently computed on a GPU cluster using the FlashAttention algorithm.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Along the main diagonal $(x,\,x,\,\dots ,\,x),$ softmax is just the uniform distribution on outputs, $(1/n,\dots ,1/n)$ : equal scores yield equal probabilities.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Geometrically, softmax is constant along diagonals: this is the dimension that is eliminated, and corresponds to the softmax output being independent of a translation in the input scores (a choice of 0 score).
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] By contrast, softmax is not invariant under scaling.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The standard logistic function is the special case for a 1-dimensional axis in 2-dimensional space, say the *x*-axis in the (x, y) plane.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function was used in statistical mechanics as the Boltzmann distribution in the foundational paper Boltzmann (1868), formalized and popularized in the influential textbook Gibbs (1902).
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The use of the softmax in decision theory is credited to R.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Duncan Luce, who used the axiom of independence of irrelevant alternatives in rational choice theory to deduce the softmax in Luce's choice axiom for relative preferences.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] In machine learning, the term "softmax" is credited to John S.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The output has most of its weight where the "4" was in the original input.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] This is what the function is normally used for: to highlight the largest values and suppress values which are significantly below the maximum value.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] But note: a change of *temperature* changes the output.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] This shows that high temperatures de-emphasize the maximum value.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] The softmax function generates probability predictions densely distributed over its support.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Other functions like sparsemax or α-entmax can be used when sparse probability predictions are desired.
[src:grouped-query-attention/softmax-function] Also the Gumbel-softmax reparametrization trick can be used when sampling from a discrete-discrete distribution needs to be mimicked in a differentiable manner.
